04233nam a22007215i 9780231530828DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20132013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2012039151  a(OCoLC)979969536  a97802315308287 a10.7312/vaug161322doi  a(DE-B1597)459409  a(OCoLC)826997368  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPN1995b.V375 2013 4aPN1995 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.43012231 aVaughan, Hunter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhere Film Meets Philosophy :bGodard, Resnais, and Experiments in Cinematic Thinking /cHunter Vaughan. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2013] 4cÂ©2013  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b42 photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFilm and Culture Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Where Film Meets Philosophy -- t1. Phenomenology and The Viewing Subject -- t2. Film Connotation And The Signified Subject -- t3. Sound, Image, And The Order Of Meaning -- t4. Alain Resnais And The Code Of Subjectivity -- t5. Jean-Luc Godard And The Code Of Objectivity -- tConclusion: Where Film And Philosophy May Lead -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHunter Vaughan interweaves phenomenology and semiotics to analyze cinema's ability to challenge conventional modes of thought. Merging Maurice Merleau-Ponty's phenomenology of perception with Gilles Deleuze's image-philosophy, Vaughan applies a rich theoretical framework to a comparative analysis of Jean-Luc Godard's films, which critique the audio-visual illusion of empirical observation (objectivity), and the cinema of Alain Resnais, in which the sound-image generates innovative portrayals of individual experience (subjectivity). Both filmmakers radically upend conventional film practices and challenge philosophical traditions to alter our understanding of the self, the world, and the relationship between the two. Films discussed in detail include Godard's Vivre sa vie (1962), Contempt (1963), and 2 or 3 Things I Know About Her (1967); and Resnais's Hiroshima, mon amour (1959), Last Year at Marienbad (1961), and The War Is Over (1966). Situating the formative works of these filmmakers within a broader philosophical context, Vaughan pioneers a phenomenological film semiotics linking two disparate methodologies to the mirrored achievements of two seemingly irreconcilable artists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aMotion picturesxPhilosophy. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/vaug1613240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231530828423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231530828/original  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK